# OSPF Multi-Area with Stub Area and External Redistribution

**Skill focus:** Multi-area OSPF design, ABRs, ASBR redistribution, stub areas, and LSA types
**Environment:** Cisco CML
**Assignment:** Build a lab mirroring the provided topology (Kadeem, Week 4). Apply stub configuration where applicable and describe the what and why of each component.

---

## Topology Overview

Two autonomous systems:

- **AS 65300** — External domain. R7 with three loopbacks (192.168.1.0/24, 192.168.2.0/24, 192.168.3.0/24), connected to AS 65400 over 205.71.1.0/24.
- **AS 65400** — The OSPF domain. R1–R6 spread across three areas.

```
AS 65300          |                      AS 65400
                  |
[R7]--205.71.1.0--[R1]---+
 loopbacks               |  switch1234 (shared segment)
 192.168.1-3.0     [R2]--+--[R3] (10.3.3.0/24)
                    |          AREA 1234 (10.123.1.0/24)
                    |
                  [R4]  ABR
                    |   AREA 0 (10.45.1.0/24)
                  [R5]  ABR
                    |   AREA 56 - STUB (10.56.1.0/24)
                  [R6]
```

---

## Component-by-Component: The What and Why

### Area 1234 — R1, R2, R3 (Multi-Access Segment)

**What:** R1, R2, and R3 all share a single network (10.123.1.0/24) through an unmanaged switch (switch1234). All three run OSPF in Area 1234.

**Why a switch:** When three or more routers share one network, they need a common Layer 2 segment to sit on. A switch provides that shared segment. (Two-router links are point-to-point and don't need a switch.)

**Why it matters:** A shared multi-access segment triggers an OSPF **DR/BDR election**. R2 became the DR and R1 the BDR, with R3 as DROTHER. The DR acts as the central point that all routers on the segment synchronize through, which avoids inefficient full-mesh LSA flooding. (DR election is non-preemptive — whoever claims DR first keeps it, even if a higher router-ID appears later.)

### R3 — Internal Router

**What:** R3 sits entirely inside Area 1234 with its own network (10.3.3.0/24).

**Why:** R3 borders no other area and connects to no external AS, so it is an internal router — the simplest OSPF role. It only advertises its networks into Area 1234.

### R4 — Area Border Router (ABR)

**What:** R4 has one interface in Area 1234 (10.24.1.0/24, facing R2) and one in Area 0 (10.45.1.0/24, facing R5).

**Why:** Because R4 has interfaces in two areas, it is an ABR. Its job is to pass routing information between Area 1234 and the backbone (Area 0), generating Type 3 Summary LSAs so each area learns the other's routes (seen as O IA — OSPF Inter-Area — routes).

### Area 0 — The Backbone

**What:** The 10.45.1.0/24 link between R4 and R5.

**Why:** Area 0 is the mandatory backbone. Every other area must connect to it. All inter-area traffic flows through Area 0, so it acts as the hub that ties Area 1234 and Area 56 together.

### R5 — Area Border Router (ABR)

**What:** R5 borders Area 0 (facing R4) and Area 56 (facing R6). It is also the router that makes Area 56 a stub and injects the default route into it.

**Why:** As the ABR into the stub, R5 controls what enters Area 56 — it blocks external LSAs and injects a single default route instead.

### R6 — Internal Router (in the Stub)

**What:** R6 is an internal router in Area 56, learning routes from R5.

**Why:** Because Area 56 is a stub, R6 does not receive individual external routes. It reaches everything outside the area through a single default route (0.0.0.0/0), which keeps its routing table small.

### R1 — Autonomous System Boundary Router (ASBR)

**What:** R1 connects to R7 in the external AS 65300. Static routes on R1 point to R7's three loopback networks, and R1 redistributes those static routes into OSPF.

**Why:** Because R1 injects external routes into the OSPF domain, it is an ASBR. The redistributed routes flow through AS 65400 as Type 5 External LSAs and appear as O E2 (OSPF External Type 2) routes on the internal routers.

