## Stub Area — The Key Demonstration

**What:** Area 56 is configured as a stub (`area 56 stub` on both R5 and R6).

**Why:** A stub area does not receive external (Type 5) LSAs. Instead of carrying every external route, the ABR (R5) injects a single default route. This keeps the routing tables of edge areas small while preserving full reachability.

**Proof (the core result):**

- On **R4** (normal area), R7's external networks appear as individual routes:
  ```
  O E2  192.168.1.0/24 [110/20] via 10.24.1.1
  O E2  192.168.2.0/24 [110/20] via 10.24.1.1
  O E2  192.168.3.0/24 [110/20] via 10.24.1.1
  ```

- On **R6** (the stub), those external routes are **absent**. Instead:
  ```
  O*IA  0.0.0.0/0 [110/2] via 10.56.1.1   (default route)
  ```

R6 can still reach the external networks — it just sends that traffic to R5 via the default route rather than storing individual entries. That contrast is the stub area doing its job.

