## LSA Types by Segment (the diagram arrows)

| Location | LSA Types Flowing | Why |
|---|---|---|
| R7 → R1 (into AS 65400) | **Type 5** (External) | R1 (ASBR) redistributes R7's external routes into OSPF |
| Within Area 1234 | **Type 1** (Router) + **Type 2** (Network) | Type 1 = each router's own links; Type 2 = DR describes the multi-access segment |
| Area 1234 → Area 0 (via R4 ABR) | **Type 1 + Type 2 + Type 3** (Summary) | Intra-area LSAs plus Type 3 generated by the ABR for inter-area routes |
| Into Area 56 (stub, via R5 ABR) | **Type 3** (Summary) + **Default Route** | Stub blocks Type 5 (external) and Type 4 (ASBR summary); ABR injects a default route instead |

**LSA type reference:**
- Type 1 (Router) — a router's own links, within an area
- Type 2 (Network) — generated by the DR on a multi-access segment
- Type 3 (Summary) — inter-area routes, generated by ABRs (O IA routes)
- Type 4 (ASBR Summary) — how to reach the ASBR (blocked in stub)
- Type 5 (External) — external routes from the ASBR (O E2 routes; blocked in stub)

